ccles, Lancashire, England","Notton, Yorkshire, England":"Notton, Jórvík, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1309–1338":"1309–1338","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1333–Female":"1333–Overleden","1340–Male":"1340–Overleden","–Female":"Overleden","1256–1310":"1256–1310","1259–Female":"1259–Overleden","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1270":"1270","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1256":"1256","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Abt 1275":"circa 1275","about 1333":"circa 1333","1309":"1309","about 1330":"circa 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Eccles, Lancashire, England":"Eccles, Lancashire, England","Notton, Yorkshire, England":"Notton, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1309–1338":"1309–1338","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1333–Female":"1333–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1256–1310":"1256–1310","1259–Female":"1259–Deceased","1330":"1330","1340":"1340","1270":"1270","1338":"1338","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1256":"1256","1333":"1333","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","Abt 1275":"about 1275","about 1333":"about 1333","1309":"1309","about 1330":"about 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Eccles, Lancashire, England":"Eccles, Lancashire, England","Notton, Yorkshire, England":"Notton, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Barton, Lancashire, England":"Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Notton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton in Lacock (Wilts) or Notton in Maiden Newton (Dorset), both of which are recorded as  <i>Natton</i> and  <i>Netton</i> in the 13th century. The place-names derive from Old English  <i>nēat</i> ‘cattle’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Noton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Natton","meanings":["English: variant of both   Notton   and   Noton  ."]},{"name":"Noton","meanings":["English: locative name from Notton (WR Yorks), which is recorded as  <i>Notone</i> in 1086 and  <i>Nocton</i> in 1230. The place-name derives from Old English  <i>hnoc</i> ‘wether sheep’ +  <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, settlement’. There has probably been some confusion with   Notton  , and perhaps also with   Knutton   and   Nocton  ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":6,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":19,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":28,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes De Notton was born in 1309, in Notton, Yorkshire, England, her father, John De Rigmaiden III, was 54 and her mother, Catherine De Pennington, was 51. She married GILBERT DE BARTON in Barton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1338, in Somme, Picardie, France, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1309–1338":"1309–1338","1270–1330":"1270–1330","1333–Female":"1333–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1256–1310":"1256–1310","1259–Female":"1259–Surnud","